deck: Assistant to Amanda Waller in the newly-redesigned Belle Reve
description:
Origin

Little is known about Bonnie's origin. At some point she took a job with the government where she eventually rose to the position of assistant warden at Belle Reve.

Creation

Bonnie was created by Sean Ryan and André Coelho. She made her first appearance in Suicide Squad #30.

Major Story Arcs

New Suicide Squad

As Amanda Waller's assistant, she aids her boss in the day-to-day operation of Belle Reve and the Suicide Squad. She gives a tour of the facility to Vic Sage, for which she is admonished by Waller, who condemns her naiveté for believing that Sage has changed or is on their side. Later, at the culmination of Sage's plot to destroy Amanda Waller, Bonnie accidentally overhears him telling Black Manta his plan to reveal the Squad to the public. She objects when he offers to let her join him in the private sector, and he shoots her in the chest, killing her.

Powers and Abilities

Bonnie has no known superhuman powers or abilities.
name: Bonnie

description:
Origin

The daughter of a refined woman from the East Coast of the United States and a miner situated in the American West. Her parents were estranged due to his search for gold, and she was raised in a sequence of boarding schools. Upon the death of her mother, she journeys to live with her father. At that point his mine is in disarray. Big Thunder Mountain is apparently fighting back by itself against the miners who try to dig deeper and deeper into the mountain in search of gold. At the same time the trains carrying the gold are under threat of being hijacked.

Creation

The character was created as the main character for the miniseries Big Thunder Mountain Railroad. The character follows a general trend for Disney to create fictional properties related to specific theme park rides.

Background

After being captured by Willikers, Chandler and Abigail are led back into town. Meanwhile in the heart of the Big Thunder Mountain, Abigail's father pleads with the workers that he has changed and that he now has the best interest of the town at heart. Onawa doesn't believe him, but he is given a chance to prove himself as he is the only train engineer with enough know-how to get the train out of the mountain. Abigail discovers that her father is in the mountain and escapes from Willikers to the inside. She manages to find her own train and hooks it up to the now out-of-commission train that her father was driving. Shortly after they discover once again that they will not make it and decide to cut loose the carts containing the gold. Willikers fights back, threatening to shoot anyone that will do so, and orders the people off the train in order to save the weight. Onawa fights back against himself, as does the physical manifestation of the mountain, and Willikers is pulled to his death, but not before Onawa is also fatally wounded. The remaining passengers manage to escape the mountain, whereafter father and daughter reconcile. He tells her that being surrounded by a greedy person like Willikers made him greedy as well and he vows to change. He also tells her that he knew that she was responsible for the train robbery. As he leaves Abigail confronts Chandler, who reveals that his first name is Jason. The two share a kiss.

Powers and Abilities

Abigail is a regular human with no superpowers. She has proven to have excellent agility on numerous occasions, as well as the ability to think on her feet with ingenious solutions. She is also an excellent horsewoman, having competed in steeplechases, and having performed acrobatics on horseback while competing.

Her horse Jagger is faster than any other horse than what most people have seen and can easily outrun a train, even over long distances.
name: Abigail Bullion

deck: Eldrac the Door is Inhuman who was submitted to Terrigen Mist and transformed into architectural-like being. His teleportation powers has helped countless Inhumans in the time of need.
description:
Origin

Eldrac was young Inhuman whom was exposed by the Terrigan mists. The mists had a profound impact on the young Inhuman, since they had changed him into a human like teleportal. He no longer had the ability to speak or walk.

Creation

Eldrac the Door was created by Jonathan Hickman and Dale Eaglesham and first appeared in Fantastic Four Vol.1 issue 577 (2010). He is one of the most original characters since he is, in reality, a living door with no ability to speak or walk.

Major Story Arcs

Seeking Help

Eldrac knew he was important for the Inhumans and helped them on a number of ocassions. He however did not like his new life as an immobile speechless gateway. When the NuHuman known as Lineage started talking to him, he convinced Eldrac to help him teleport the royal family away from New Attilan, and in return he would receive a robot body, which would give him the abbility to walk once more. Eldrac accepted and send the Inhuman Royal Family and friends to a place where they where awaited by enemies. Lineage had followed through on his word and managed to make a robot body for Eldrac, causing him to walk again. As soon as he had the chance, Eldrac walked out on Lineage and found a quite place at the water near New York City. There, Eldrac, feeling remorse and coming to realize what he had done, opened up his portal again. He then put his own robot hands through the portal and grabbed the Inhuman royal family at the place he had left them. He took them through his portal once more and eventually returned them home safe to new Atillan. Eldrac remained by the waters he had run of to. Then, wanting nothing to do with Lineage anymore, he tore his own head lose from it's robot body, causing Eldrac to fall on the ground near the waters where he had been standing only moments ago.

issue_credits.name: Prime Elements 4: The Cult of Negative Zone

name: Eldrac
